# Food truck activation kit D: subscription and discount tier model

**Status:** READY FOR FOUNDER REVIEW
**Authored:** 2026-06-10
**Author:** Bishop SEG-SUB-MODEL (Sonnet 4.6, Statute §3)
**Canonical app name:** Atlas (scheduling app)
**Feeds into:** Kit B (customer walkthrough), Kit C (operator setup)

---

## §1: The decision in one sentence

**Order and pay in advance, you get a discount. The further forward you commit, the better the deal.**

This is not a coupon scheme. Coupons are extractive: the platform or the food truck eats the loss so a customer feels like they got one over on somebody. This is different. When a customer commits to three meals before they eat them, or twelve meals before the month begins, the food truck gains something concrete and valuable: they know what to buy at the grocery market Tuesday morning instead of guessing. They buy exactly what they need, not twenty percent extra as a buffer. They waste less food. They can schedule their helper for the right days and send them home on the slow days. They have cash in hand before they fire up the propane.

The discount is the customer's share of the planning win. The food truck is not giving something away. They are paying the customer back in savings for the operational certainty the customer just handed them. The Liana Banyan platform enables the commitment mechanism (Atlas scheduling, advance payment escrow, week-start disbursement), takes Cost+20% as its platform margin on every transaction, and workers, builders, and creators keep 83.3%.

**Platform margin note (ratified 2026-06-10):** The Cost+20% platform margin is structural. It is always baked into the customer price. Tier discounts come from the food truck's 83.3% share, not from LB's 16.7% platform margin. The food truck offers the discount in exchange for advance commitment, the planning win, and the cash-flow timing advantage. LB's 16.7% is constant on all three tiers.

When a member places a forward commitment, that act of planned participation also earns Marks in the cooperative-class ledger, separate from the dollar discount on this transaction. (See §6 for the cooperative-class framing.)

---

## §2: Recommended tier structure

### How the pricing baseline works

The Liana Banyan platform runs on Cost+20%. That means the customer pays the food truck's listed menu price, and the platform takes 16.7% of that total (1/1.20 = 0.833 keeper share). The food truck keeps 83.3 cents of every dollar the customer pays.

For the math below, a representative meal is priced at $13.50 on the platform. The food truck receives $11.25 per meal. Cost of goods (ingredients, packaging) for a typical food-truck meal at that price point runs approximately $9.00 (about 67% of what the food truck receives, or about 66% of what the customer pays). That leaves approximately $2.25 per meal for labor, overhead, and margin before discounts.

These are representative numbers. The operator tool in §5 lets each food truck enter their actual COGS percentage and receive a dynamically computed max-discount recommendation.

---

### Tier 1: Order now (single meal, today)

| | |
|---|---|
| **What you commit** | One meal, for today |
| **When you pay** | At delivery |
| **What you save** | Nothing (full menu price) |
| **Example (per meal)** | Customer pays $13.50 / food truck receives $11.25 / platform receives $2.25 |
| **Best for** | First-time customers, one-off visits, customers not yet on a plan |

Tier 1 is the baseline. No advance commitment, no discount, no cooperative mechanics engaged. The customer orders, shows up, eats, pays. This tier is open to any customer, member or not. It establishes the reference price that all discounts are measured against.

**Food truck economics at Tier 1:**
- Customer pays: $13.50
- Food truck receives: $11.25 (83.3%)
- Platform receives: $2.25 (16.7%)
- Food truck COGS (estimate): $9.00
- Food truck margin (gross): ~$2.25/meal (approximately 16.7% of menu price, before labor and overhead)
- This is tight but typical for a food truck with good volume. Labor and overhead are the remaining squeeze.

---

### Tier 2: Week plan (3 meals this week)

| | |
|---|---|
| **What you commit** | 3 meals, to be eaten within the current week (7 days from first meal) |
| **When you pay** | 50% upfront at time of commitment; remainder split across meal deliveries or paid in a single end-of-week settlement |
| **What you save** | 15% off the menu total for all 3 meals |
| **Advance notice required** | Customer commits at least 24 hours before the first meal |
| **LB membership required** | Yes. $5/year member account required to access Atlas scheduling and forward-commitment tiers. Non-members see a "Join LB ($5/year) to unlock this plan" CTA at checkout. |

**Customer math (representative):**
- Walk-up price per meal: $13.50
- Tier 2 price per meal: $13.50 × 85% = **$11.47**
- Total for 3 meals: $34.42 (vs $40.50 walk-up)
- Customer saves: $6.08 across 3 meals
- Upfront payment at commitment: $17.21
- Remaining payment: $17.21 (spread across meal pickups or end-of-week)

**Food truck economics at Tier 2:**
- Food truck receives: 83.3% × $34.42 = **$28.67 total / $9.55 per meal**
- Food truck COGS (estimate, 3 meals): ~$27.00
- Food truck gross margin: ~$1.67 total / ~$0.56 per meal
- Cash-flow win: $14.31 of food truck revenue arrives at week-start, before cooking begins
- Planning win: ingredient purchase is known 24+ hours in advance; waste from over-purchasing drops

**Truth-Always note on Tier 2 margin:** at typical food-truck economics, $0.56/meal gross margin before labor and overhead is thin. The planning win needs to translate into real savings (less waste, tighter labor scheduling) for Tier 2 to be profitable. For food trucks with above-average efficiency or lower local ingredient costs, Tier 2 works well. See §5 for the operator discount calculator.

---

### Tier 3: Month plan (12 meals across 4 weeks)

| | |
|---|---|
| **What you commit** | 12 meals across 4 weeks (approximately 3 meals per week); customer picks which days when committing |
| **When you pay** | Full prepayment at time of commitment |
| **What you save** | Up to 20% off the menu total for all 12 meals (dynamically set per operator COGS; max is 20%) |
| **LB membership required** | Yes. $5/year member account required. Non-members see a "Join LB ($5/year) to unlock this plan" CTA at checkout. |

**Customer math (representative):**
- Walk-up price per meal: $13.50
- Tier 3 price per meal: $13.50 × 80% = **$10.80**
- Total for 12 meals: $129.60 (vs $162.00 walk-up)
- Customer saves: $32.40 across 12 meals
- All $129.60 paid at commitment

**Food truck economics at Tier 3:**
- Food truck receives: 83.3% × $129.60 = **$107.96 total / $9.00 per meal**
- Food truck COGS (estimate, 12 meals): ~$108.00
- Food truck gross margin at typical COGS: **approximately $0 before labor and overhead**
- Cash-flow win: substantial: full month's revenue for these 12 meals is in hand at signup; 50% of each week's portion disbursed at week-start (see §3)
- Planning win: four weeks of ingredient purchasing planned in advance; bulk buying becomes realistic; labor scheduling locked four weeks out

**Truth-Always note on Tier 3 margin:** Tier 3 at 20% discount is a break-even proposition for a typical food truck at $9 COGS/meal. The value proposition for the food truck is NOT the per-meal margin on these customers; it is the cash certainty, the planning horizon, and the customer loyalty that comes from a month-long commitment. A food truck operator who fills 30% of their weekly volume on Tier 3 Month Plans can plan their ingredient purchases weeks out, eliminate most over-purchase waste, and use that waste savings to offset the thin per-meal margin.

For food trucks with very low margins (COGS above 45% of menu price), 20% off may cause losses. See §5 for the dynamic calculator.

**The max-discount recommendation for Tier 3 is computed dynamically based on the operator's stated COGS percentage.** If a food truck's economics are tighter than the representative example, Tier 3 might be offered at 15% off. If the food truck is a premium operator with strong margins, Tier 3 could offer up to 20% off (hard cap) while staying profitable. The system computes this at onboarding and lets the owner adjust within safe bounds. The 20% cap is a hard ceiling regardless of margin strength.

---

### Tier structure summary

| | Tier 1: Order now | Tier 2: Week plan | Tier 3: Month plan |
|---|---|---|---|
| Meals committed | 1 | 3 this week | 12 over 4 weeks |
| Discount | None | 15% off | 20% off |
| Customer pays (per meal, example) | $13.50 | $11.47 | $10.80 |
| Payment timing | At delivery | 50% now, 50% over week | All upfront |
| Food truck receives (per meal) | $11.25 | $9.55 | $9.00 |
| Food truck cash-flow win | None | Half-week revenue early | Full month revenue early |
| Planning win for food truck | None | 3-meal window | 4-week window |
| LB membership required | No (open to any customer) | Yes ($5/year) | Yes ($5/year) |
| Atlas scheduling required | No | Yes | Yes |

---

## §3: How this composes with the "food truck gets paid half upfront each week" rule

Founder's spec states: the food truck gets half of the week's revenue at week-start, before they cook.

Here is how the three tiers map to that disbursement rule:

**Tier 1 customers** pay at delivery. There is no advance cash for the food truck from Tier 1 orders. Week-start disbursement does not apply to Tier 1. The food truck receives payment only after the meal is served.

**Tier 2 customers** prepay 50% at the time they commit (which is at least 24 hours before the first meal). Atlas holds that 50% and disburses it to the food truck at the start of the week. The remaining 50% is collected across meal pickups or as a single end-of-week settlement and disbursed immediately on collection. The food truck's effective experience: they start the week with approximately half their Tier 2 revenue already in hand, before cooking begins.

**Tier 3 customers** prepay 100% at commitment, which may be up to four weeks in advance. Atlas holds the full prepayment in escrow and releases it in weekly tranches: at each week-start, 50% of that week's portion (3 meals × $10.80 × 83.3% = $26.99 per week, 50% = ~$13.50) is disbursed to the food truck. The remaining 50% of each week's portion is released on delivery of each meal or as a weekly settlement. The food truck receives a predictable cash-flow installment every Monday (or equivalent week-start day) for four consecutive weeks.

**Net effect:** Tier 2 and Tier 3 customers both produce early cash for the food truck, consistent with Founder's spec. Tier 1 customers do not. A food truck that builds a Tier 2 + Tier 3 base of regulars begins each week with reliable revenue before a single meal is cooked. That is the cooperative-class cash-flow architecture.

**Wave B requirement (flag):** The escrow, week-start disbursement schedule, and per-meal release logic described here requires Atlas scheduling integration with payment processing. This is a Wave B build requirement. In Wave A (initial launch), a simplified version (manual disbursement record or single weekly transfer) can stand in, clearly marked as manual. Flag to Founder and Knight when Wave B scoping begins.

