## §5: Food-truck-owner economic decision aid

*Drop-in for Kit C operator setup. Presented to the food truck owner when they configure their discount tiers inside Atlas.*

---

### What discount can I actually afford?

The table below shows the maximum discount you can offer on Tier 2 and Tier 3 while still keeping at least $0.50 per meal in gross margin after the Liana Banyan platform fee (16.7% of customer price).

These numbers assume the LB Cost+20% baseline pricing (food truck listed price = menu price; customer pays that price; LB takes 16.7%; food truck keeps 83.3%).

Tier 3 hard cap is **20% off** regardless of margin. Ratification 2026-06-10.

| Your COGS as % of menu price (approx) | COGS example on $13.50 meal | Tier 2 max discount | Tier 3 max discount | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| ~25% of menu price | ~$3.38 | 20% off | 20% off (hard cap) | Premium margin. Compelling offer, well within safe band. |
| ~35% of menu price | ~$4.73 | 15% off | 20% off (hard cap) | Healthy margin. Full Tier 3 cap available. |
| ~45% of menu price | ~$6.08 | 12% off | 15% off | Moderate margin. Tier 3 capped at 15% for safety. |
| ~55% of menu price | ~$7.43 | 8% off | 10% off | Tight margin. Discounts rely on planning wins to break even. Focus on Tier 1 + volume. |
| ~67% of menu price (typical food truck) | ~$9.00 | 15% off | 18% off | Representative baseline used throughout this document. Tier 3 at 18% is the computed safe ceiling at typical COGS before planning-win offset. |

**Note:** The 20% Tier 3 cap is a hard ceiling ratified 2026-06-10. Atlas will not allow a Tier 3 discount above 20% regardless of stated COGS. The dynamic calculator sets the safe discount within that ceiling; it can only recommend lower, never higher.

---

**How to read this table**

Your COGS percentage is the single biggest lever. If you spend 80 cents of every dollar you receive on ingredients and packaging, you have 20 cents left to cover labor, overhead, and profit before any discount. A 15% discount on a $13.50 meal reduces your received amount from $11.25 to $9.55. If your COGS is $9.00 on that meal, you have $0.55 left. That is your planning-win buffer: if you save $0.55 or more per meal by buying exactly what you need instead of guessing, you break even or better.

**These are maximum discounts, not required discounts.** You can always offer less. A 10% discount on Tier 2 is still meaningful to a regular customer and is safer for operators with tighter margins.

**The planning win is real.** Most food truck operators report that food waste runs 8 to 15% of ingredient cost when they buy by feel. If you know Tuesday you are cooking 12 bowls, you buy for 12 bowls. At $9.00 COGS and 10% waste reduction, you save $0.90/meal. That alone more than offsets a 10% Tier 2 discount. The discount is not charity to the customer; it is the customer paying you for the certainty they just gave you.

**How Atlas sets this up:** when you register your food truck, Atlas asks for your estimated COGS percentage. It then computes a Tier 2 and Tier 3 max discount for you and pre-fills the discount fields with a conservative safe starting point. You can move the sliders up or down within the safe band. The band is enforced so you cannot accidentally set a discount that causes you to lose money at typical COGS. If your actual COGS changes (seasonal ingredients, new supplier), you update your COGS estimate and the safe band recalculates.

---

### The cash-flow math in plain language

Even when the per-meal margin is thin at Tier 3, consider what the cash-flow advance is worth:

A food truck doing 100 meals per week at $13.50 has roughly $1,125 in weekly food truck revenue. If 30 of those meals are Tier 3 Month Plan customers, the food truck receives 50% of those 30 meals' revenue ($30 × $10.80 × 83.3% × 50% = ~$135) on Monday morning before they cook a single meal. Across a month that is four Monday installments plus delivery-day releases. That is the difference between buying ingredients on credit and buying ingredients with cash in hand.

Cash in hand before cooking is worth more than the per-meal discount costs. That is the food truck economics case for offering Tier 3 even at thin margins.

---

## §6: The cooperative-class framing (the load-bearing why)

Coupons are extractive. A coupon says: the platform, the brand, or the restaurant will absorb a loss so this customer feels like they won something. The customer pays less, the platform takes its cut regardless, and the food truck eats the difference. That is extraction dressed up as generosity.

This tier model is designed differently. When a customer commits to three meals or twelve meals in advance, they are not exploiting a discount code. They are providing something the food truck cannot manufacture on their own: certainty. Certainty about volume. Certainty about timing. Certainty that translates directly into better purchasing decisions, less waste, and the ability to schedule labor without guessing.

The discount is the food truck's payment to the customer for the certainty the customer just gave them. The food truck decides what that certainty is worth to them, within the bounds Atlas computes. The platform does not set the discount. The food truck does.

On the Liana Banyan platform, the act of committing forward is also a form of cooperative-class participation. When a member places a Tier 2 or Tier 3 commitment, that forward commitment earns Marks in the cooperative-class ledger. Marks are separate from the dollar discount: the discount is immediate, on this transaction, from the food truck's planning win. The Marks accrue to the customer's participation record on the platform and can be spent on cooperative privileges, contribute to governance weight, and reflect the member's history of cooperative-class behavior (forward commitment, advance payment, reduced waste production).

The food truck is not punished for offering bigger discounts to Tier 3 customers. They are rewarded: earlier cash, longer planning horizon, customer loyalty that compounds. The Liana Banyan platform takes the same Cost+20% margin on all three tiers. There is no platform tax on cooperative behavior. Workers, builders, and creators keep 83.3%.

*Note on Marks implementation: the Marks ledger for forward-commitment participation is ratified canon as of 2026-06-10. Marks accrue to the customer's participation record in the cooperative-class ledger. They compose with the three-currency canon (Credits/Marks/Joules, never convertible to fiat). Wave C scope item: implement Marks accrual logic in Atlas for Tier 2 and Tier 3 forward commitments.*

---

## §7: Truth-Always notes for Founder

Eight honest surfaces. No softening.

---

**1. Founder's "50% off" number does not pencil for typical food-truck margins.**

At the representative baseline ($13.50 menu price, $11.25 food truck receives, ~$9.00 COGS), a 50% customer discount means the customer pays $6.75. The food truck receives 83.3% of that: $5.62. COGS is still ~$9.00. The food truck loses $3.37 per meal, before labor and overhead. That is not a thin margin situation; that is a guaranteed operating loss on every discounted meal.

50% off is not viable unless:
- The food truck has exceptional margins (COGS below 40% of menu price, which is unusual)
- The bulk-buy and planning savings exceed $3.37/meal, which is extraordinarily unlikely for advance notice measured in days

Bishop recommends: the maximum discount in the tier model should be **20% off for Tier 3** (12-meal monthly commitment), dynamically adjusted down for lower-margin operators. 20% is still a compelling customer offer ("buy 12 meals, the cost is what 9.6 meals would have been") and can be profitable for typical operators when combined with planning wins.

---

**2. "Cost+20%" interpretation: RESOLVED (ratified 2026-06-10).**

The Cost+20% platform margin is structural and always baked into the customer price. Subscription/Tier 2/Tier 3 customers pay the same baseline menu price as walk-up customers (already the Cost+20% platform price), with the tier discount applied on top of that. The discount comes out of the food truck's 83.3% share. LB's 16.7% platform margin is not discounted on any tier. This is confirmed and no longer requires Founder input.

---

**3. "The third meal is nearly free": RESOLVED (ratified 2026-06-10).**

The "slightly more than one meal" framing does not match the math and is no longer used in any kit copy. At 20% off for 3 meals, the customer pays $32.40 vs $40.50 walk-up. That is 2.4 meals' worth of cost for 3 meals. The canonical customer-facing framing is: "the third meal is nearly free." This is accurate and more compelling. All kit copy uses this framing.

---

**4. Atlas is the canonical name for the scheduling app: confirmed in the brief.**

Atlas is confirmed as the canonical scheduling app name. Used throughout this document. If there is any ambiguity in source code or platform copy still using "MnemosyneC Scheduler" or another label, flag for Knight to clean up.

---

**5. Marks-for-forward-commitment: RESOLVED (ratified 2026-06-10).**

Placing a Tier 2 or Tier 3 commitment earns Marks in the cooperative-class ledger, separate from the dollar discount. This is now canon. Marks are not fiat-convertible. They accrue to the customer's cooperative-class participation record. Knight Wave C scope item: implement Marks accrual logic in Atlas for Tier 2 and Tier 3 forward commitments.

---

**6. Tier 2 and Tier 3 require Atlas to handle "customer picks days within the week or month."**

The customer-facing day-selection flow (pick Tuesday, Thursday, and Friday this week; pick specific days across a month) is calendar and scheduling logic that Atlas needs to support. This is a Wave B requirement. In Wave A, a simplified version (customer notes their preferred days in text; food truck confirms manually) can stand in. Flag for Knight and Wave B scoping.

---

**7. No-show and cancellation policy: RESOLVED (ratified 2026-06-10).**

Missed meals roll forward up to 7 days from the scheduled date, then forfeit to the community pool. The community pool funds free meals for SNAP recipients and food-insecure community members. This is canon. It is clear to the customer, consistent with cooperative-class values, and creates a positive narrative around forfeiture ("your skipped meal fed your neighbor"). This policy applies to Tier 2 and Tier 3 prepaid commitments. Tier 1 (order now) has no prepaid meal to roll forward. Atlas Wave B: implement roll-forward logic and community pool tracking.

---

**8. Tier 1 (Order now) is accessible to non-members. Tier 2 and Tier 3 require LB membership: RESOLVED (ratified 2026-06-10).**

Tier 1 is open to any customer, member or not. Tier 2 and Tier 3 require an LB membership ($5/year). The cooperative-class commitment machinery (Marks ledger, advance payment escrow, week-start disbursement) is member-bound.

At checkout for a Tier 2 or Tier 3 commitment, Atlas surfaces the $5/year membership offer inline for non-members: "Join Liana Banyan ($5/year) to unlock this plan and start saving." Heart-of-Peace voice, not scarcity-FOMO. One tap, no friction. This is the access model for all kit copy.

