## Appendix — Tier math verification (full working)

*For Founder's spot-check. All figures are representative; actual operator economics vary.*

**Baseline assumptions:**
- Menu price (LB platform): $13.50 per meal
- LB platform fee: 16.7% (= 1 - 83.3%)
- Food truck receives: 83.3% × $13.50 = $11.25
- LB receives: 16.7% × $13.50 = $2.25
- Representative COGS per meal: $9.00 (= 67% of food truck receipts = 66.7% of menu price)
- Representative gross margin before discount, per meal: $11.25 - $9.00 = $2.25

**Tier 1 (no discount):**
- Customer pays: $13.50
- Food truck: $11.25 received, $9.00 COGS, $2.25 gross margin per meal
- Platform: $2.25

**Tier 2 (15% off, 3 meals):**
- Per meal: $13.50 × 85% = $11.47 customer pays
- Food truck per meal: $11.47 × 83.3% = $9.55 received; $9.00 COGS; $0.55 gross margin
- 3 meals total: food truck receives $28.67; customer pays $34.42; platform receives $5.75
- Customer savings vs 3× Tier 1: $40.50 - $34.42 = $6.08

**Tier 3 (20% off, 12 meals):**
- Per meal: $13.50 × 80% = $10.80 customer pays
- Food truck per meal: $10.80 × 83.3% = $9.00 received; $9.00 COGS; $0.00 gross margin (break even before planning wins)
- 12 meals total: food truck receives $107.96; customer pays $129.60; platform receives $21.64
- Customer savings vs 12× Tier 1: $162.00 - $129.60 = $32.40

**Founder's original "50% off" scenario:**
- Per meal: $13.50 × 50% = $6.75 customer pays
- Food truck per meal: $6.75 × 83.3% = $5.62 received; $9.00 COGS; **loss of $3.37 per meal**
- Food truck total loss on 3 such meals: $10.12 before labor or overhead
- Verdict: does not pencil. See §7, item 1.

